##Special Report | how Britain, with its "herd immunity" , coped with the new Crown Storm

Hi, Monica and Monica

Function description, here is the "First Finance" magazine (predecessor "first finance weekly") readers club, we discover wonderful business value for you, also invited you to explore the bright business world.

Intern reporter | Wen Simin

Editor | NI NI

For now, Naomi, who lives in Edinburgh, Scotland, feels helpless.

Naomi is from Taiwan and has lived in the UK for nearly seven years. Her husband, James, is a native Scot. From March 7, James began to experience coughing, fever, neck pain, shortness of breath, and general weakness -- nine out of 10 new pneumonia symptoms, according to Harvard Medical School.

The couple immediately called the 111 medical line, and after asking about the situation, the medical staff said James did not have a confirmed case and did not return from the affected area and did not need to be tested. "You shouldn't have an infection, don't worry, " said the medical officer on the other end of the line.

Naomi wanted her husband isolated at home, but he didn't take it seriously at first, didn't want to wear a mask, and even went to bars, concerts, soccer games, stand-up shows and other public places as usual.

"people have a very different idea that this is the flu, or the flu with more severe symptoms, " Naomi told Yimagazine.

To make matters worse, the day after her husband developed symptoms, their 14 month old daughter, Harry, also developed a high fever. Naomi took her to the emergency room, but the doctor did only basic tests and prescribed anti inflammatories and antibiotics.

Within a week of both her husband and daughter showing symptoms, Naomi not only called the 111 medical line, she also spoke to her family doctor. Please report to the Emergency Department of a major hospital. However, after many setbacks to the hospital, the emergency department door posted a notice: People with COVID-19 symptoms are not allowed to enter, please go home quarantine.

On March 12th the Boris Johnson, Britain's prime minister, set out a counterpoint to most other countries in the face of the spread of new Crown Disease in Europe: If 60% of Britain's population (about 40m people) were infected with the disease, and be immunized after recovery, the virus can be completely cut off, the British will all be safe, that is, the so-called "herd immunity. ". There will be no suspension of classes or banning of gatherings, patients with mild symptoms will be quarantined at home for only a week and will not be tested for the virus, and the government's only advice is to wash hands and be vigilant.

The last time Naomi called her family doctor, the call was finally forwarded to Scotland's largest children's hospital, which, after a four hour wait, offered to see Harry.

The Children's Hospital's emergency department was very different from the one Naomi had gone to. The hospital space had been split in two and a separate area had been set up for new cases. Here, paramedics donned protective clothing and wrapped themselves from head to toe. "It's all isolation rooms, the doors are closed, and you can only hear some children crying. "

The doctor said that Harry was in good spirits and capacity, and that there was no need for tests or blood taking. He was advised to come back when his condition became serious. Doctors told Naomi that most people will be infected in the near future, and that testing will not change the way hospitals treat their patients, and that patients will still be sent home to be quarantined because there is no cure for the virus and the body has to fight it on its own, hospitals only take people who are really sick.

Not surprisingly, the "group immunity" speech out in the world immediately caused a great controversy. On March 14th a group of 229 scientists from British universities published an open letter expressing concern about the government's actions. Anthony Costello, director of the Institute of Global Health at University College London, also posted a stream of questions on Twitter. "will this undermine our efforts to contain the epidemic and lead to more infections and deaths in the near term? " Read One? There is evidence that both early and asymptomatic infections lead to large-scale transmission of the virus."

An open letter from 229 British scientists

On March 16th, amid the spread of the epidemic and public outcry, Johnson stepped up control measures: If one person in the family developed symptoms such as fever and cough, the whole family should be isolated from themselves for 14 days and urged to avoid unnecessary interpersonal contact, stopping non-essential travel, avoiding crowded places, working from home, and so on, doesn't actually overturn the idea of herd immunity. Patrick Vallance, the British government's chief scientific adviser, who first described the concept in public, was forced to say that "herd immunity" would be a side effect of an epidemic rather than a direct strategy.

The Boris Johnson speaks during a news conference on the outbreak on March 16. | PHOTO: Xinhua

As of 9:00 AM local time on March 18, the cumulative total of newly diagnosed cases of pneumonia in the UK stands at 2,626, with 676 new cases reported in the past 24 hours. Three days ago, the BBC reported that the estimated number of people infected in the UK was between 35,000 and 50,000.

The number of passengers on the tube dropped significantly during the morning rush hour in London on Monday, March 16. | PHOTO: Xinhua

The average Briton is not unafraid of an epidemic. Liam Smith, a Briton who works at a nursing home in London, said there was a shortage of toilet paper in British supermarkets and it was hard to find paracetamol and hand sanitizer in pharmacies. "Last Saturday, you found people still going to bars. This Saturday, I don't think anyone will go to bars again. "

A picture of an elderly man checking a shopping list against an empty shelf at a supermarket in Surrey has been widely shared on social media in the UK. Many people are calling for a stop to the rush caused by the new pneumonia.

But, Smith says, "herd immunity" is misunderstood by many. "That's because of the overwhelming scale of the epidemic, " Liam told Yimagazine. "Of course, on a large scale, most people think it's ridiculous. "

In fact, the epidemic prevention in Britain is closely related to its epidemic prevention strategy. On March 3rd the Department of Health released its COVID-19, a document that spells out the UK authorities'plan to fight the new coronavirus -- dubbed Florida -- in four stages

Phase one: control. Detect early cases, track close contacts, and prevent the spread of the disease throughout the country.
Phase 2: Delay. Slowing the spread of the virus, if successful, could delay the peak of the epidemic to avoid winter effects.
Phase 3: Research. Understand the virus to reduce the impact on the population; improve innovation, including in Diagnostics, drugs and vaccines; and seek the most effective coping models.
Phase 4: DÃ©tente. To provide care and support to those infected, the government will take measures to ease the pressure on health-care institutions to ensure the provision of necessary medical services. It will also minimise the impact on society, public services and the economy.

As the number of people infected in the UK has increased, this means that early containment of the virus is no longer possible. Therefore, according to the "Epidemic Prevention Action Plan" , the United Kingdom is now beginning to adopt the second phase of the "delay" strategy. Its main idea is to delay the arrival of the peak value by taking measures as if it will co-exist with the virus for a long time, in order to flatten the peak curve of the number of infected people.

In the wake of the controversy over herd immunity, UK Health Secretary Matt Hancock wrote in the Telegraph on March 14th: Herd Immunity is not part of our plan. This is a scientific concept, neither a goal nor a strategy. Our goal is to protect lives from this virus, to protect the most vulnerable, and to protect the National Health Service through containment, delay, research and mitigation.

The NHS is the name given to the public health system in England, Scotland, Wales and Ireland. It began with the rise of welfare reforms after the Second World War, designed to provide universal and free health care for all. For a long time, the NHS was the country's proudest asset. It has long been hailed as one of the best healthcare systems in the world for its fairness, free for all, and leading quality of care and management.

Because private hospitals are expensive, the NHS is the main artery of the British health system, on which most of the nation's care depends. Inevitably, how to keep the NHS running smoothly has been at the heart of Britain's fight against the disease.

In his article, Hancock says bluntly: "We have to protect the vulnerable, protect the NHS, and level the curve. " The reason for the urgent need to level the curve is that the current vulnerability of the NHS is simply not enough to cope with the surge in risk of new coronary pneumonia. So Britain adopted the strategy of catching the serious disease and releasing the mild disease.

Apart from the lack of supplies and staff, a doctor's tale: We don't have masks, goggles and staff, the Guardian said in an oral health care article published on March 15, the hospital has a 98% full-staff rate and is "social sick" , who have yet to be discharged and have nowhere to go, which means the virus is on the doorstep, hospitals don't have room for the new coronary patients that are coming in.

About 560,000 beds and 93,000 ventilators are needed to deal with new coronavirus infections, according to the Telegraph. The reality is that there are fewer than 150,000 beds in the NHS, of which only 4,000 are in intensive care, and the proportion of beds in the NHS is now 83 per cent. Figures from the NHS confirm this: In the week to 16 February, the average bed occupancy rate in 132 NHS hospitals in the UK was 94 per cent -- as was the case before the outbreak, many hospitals don't have beds anymore.

High occupancy rates are the norm in the UK health system. Globally, the UK has the lowest rate of hospital beds per person. According to figures published on the OECD's website, the UK had just 2.5 beds for every 1,000 people in 2017. Especially in winter, when influenza is prevalent, the occupancy rate can reach 95% .

G7 countries have hospital beds per 1,000 people in 2017. | Source: Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) . More statistics on the average number of beds per thousand in other OECD countries can be found here.

In addition, the British government can not directly free requisition of private hospital beds. The opposition Labour Party has proposed to the prime minister that 8,000 beds in Britain's 570 private hospitals be taken over by the opposition Labour Union to ease the pressure on the NHS. However, this is still a drop in the bucket for the tens of thousands of patients who are about to be diagnosed.

Paying for a private hospital is also a considerable expense, with an estimated cost of 300 pounds per bed per night, which means that the cost of a bed alone, the British government will spend about 2.4 million pounds (19.71 million yuan) a day.

Naomi is not alone in her frustration with the British health care system. According to the 2019 British social attitudes survey, satisfaction with the NHS has been on the decline since 2010.

Satisfaction with the NHS has been on the decline since 2010. | Chart Source: The King's Fund.

Long visits, intractable deficits, year after year budget cuts, and the loss of health care workers have left a system that has operated for 70 years on a socialized medicine model, the ruling conservatives and labour have long debated whether to privatise some hospitals under the NHS.

"The battle against the epidemic will be a test of whether the NHS can be more effective if it is privatised, and whether it succeeds or fails is a gun for both parties. From the conservative point of view, they are now trying to avoid a run on medical resources,"contemporary British political researcher Yang Yang told First Finance Yimagzine, "The NHS may be overwhelmed by a healthcare squeeze, and the negative effects of the Tories' reduced spending on the NHS over the past decade will be immediately apparent. "

Predictably, if the NHS's problems do not improve in the short term, the UK will be left on the path of "herd immunity" , whether it wants to or not. More experts pointed out that the United Kingdom from Italy's current state of about less than four weeks.

On the evening of March 18, Johnson announced at the press conference of the new crown epidemic that starting from Friday (20th) , with the exception of the children of a few key frontline epidemic prevention workers and some vulnerable groups of children, they can continue to go to school, all schools and kindergartens in England have been closed and entrance exams for May and June have been cancelled. On the morning of the 18th, the Scottish and Welsh governments have decided to suspend schools.

Time is running out for the UK, which has become increasingly proactive in its policies and practices.
